player.seasonOutlook: Jokic is good for a consistent 20 points and 10 rebounds, while shooting over 50% from the field; elite big-man numbers. Simultaneously, he has two straight seasons of at least 7.0 APG, 1.0 SPG, 1.0 3PG and 80 FT%; like an elite guard. That unique combination gives Jokic a legitimate case for the top overall pick in fantasy drafts, and at only 25 years old, he could still be getting better.

Simmons struggled with injuries last season, missing 16 regular season games and the entire playoffs after having missed only four games total in the previous two seasons. Simmons is reportedly healthy heading into this season, and more importantly, the team is set up to maximize his contributions. Simmons is not a shooter, but he uses his excellent size and athletic ability to finish at high efficiency around the rim while profiling as a nightly triple-double threat with excellent defensive stats. By bringing in pure 3-point shooters like Danny Green and Seth Curry, the 76ers maximized Simmons' space to work while simultaneously giving him excellent finishers with whom to distribute the ball and generate assists.

Ingram was the Most Improved Player in the NBA last season, turning in huge career highs of 23.8 PPG, 6.1 RPG, 4.2 APG, 2.4 3PG and 1.0 SPG, as one of the most productive players in the NBA. Ingram and Zion Williamson are the franchise centerpieces for the Pelicans, and with Jrue Holiday gone, they will be relied upon even more heavily for team offense creation. Still only 23 years old, look for Ingram to continue to improve this season with a well-deserved fantasy draft grade in the top few rounds.

Murray posted the best numbers of his career last season, but his story took a sharp twist toward greatness when he posted one of the best performances by any perimeter player in the NBA playoffs. Murray averaged 26.5 PPG (50.5 FG%, 89.7 FT%), 6.6 APG, 4.8 RPG and 3.3 3PG during 19 postseason contests on a run to the Western Conference Finals. These numbers would be much better than his career bests, but he maintained them for the equivalent of a quarter of an NBA season, which indicates these numbers could be a realistic ceiling for the 23-year-old in his fifth season.

Covington is one of the more underrated players in the NBA, consistently making a large impact on offense with his ability to knock down volume 3-pointers with strong efficiency from the frontcourt, and an even larger impact on defense with his excellent rotations and athleticism. This translates to large numbers in unique categories, as Covington averaged 2.4 3PG, 2.2 BPG and 1.6 SPG during 22 games after joining the Rockets last season. He has the potential to approach each of those marks with the Trail Blazers this season, while also scoring in the low-to-mid double-digits. This unique combination makes him an early/mid-round prospect in fantasy drafts, particularly in roto leagues.

Lowry took on a larger scoring role last season, adding 5.2 PPG to his ledger compared to the previous season, when the Raptors' offense had run through Kawhi Leonard. Lowry's 7.5 APG were the second-highest average of his career, though slightly lower than the season before. Lowry missed 14 games last season after missing 17 the season prior, and he will turn 35 years old during this season, so he is a bit of an injury risk moving forward. With that said, he combined with Fred VanVleet to form one of the best backcourts in the NBA and, health permitting, they should reprise that value again this season.

Oladipo missed the majority of last season as he recovered from a torn quad tendon, and when he returned, he was clearly rusty and unable to produce anywhere near the level that had once made him an All-Star. There are rumors that he is unhappy with the Pacers and would like to be traded, but Oladipo has publicly denied those rumors. If healthy, he has the opportunity to bounce back as another plus scorer in the Pacers' balanced attack. He seems unlikely to regain his former primacy, but his potential to score in the upper-teens with solid efficiency and good all-around numbers make him a solid mid-round prospect, even with the injury questions.

Randle was the centerpiece of an odd Knicks free-agency plan last offseason, as the best of four starting caliber power forwards that they signed. Randle had a strong season, decimal points removed from averaging 20-10 on the season, and also contributed a few assists, a 3-pointer and almost a steal per game. Much of that glut of power forwards has moved on from the Knicks, and Randle's style seemingly complements new starting center Mitchell Robinson. He should come off the board by the late-early/early-middle rounds of fantasy drafts, with more value in points leagues than roto.

Harrell is the reigning NBA Sixth Man of the Year for his work with the Clippers and looks to reprise that role this season after moving across the hallway of the Staples Center to join the Lakers. Harrell is an outstanding finisher with a career 61.4 FG% and is coming off career bests last season of 18.6 PPG and 7.1 RPG. He was the dominant big man for the Clippers last season, even though he came off the bench. However, on the Lakers, he will clearly be subordinate to Anthony Davis and have further competition from new center Marc Gasol. This could eat into Harrell's scoring volume a bit, which hinders his upside because he gets most of his fantasy value from his combination of scoring volume and efficiency. Nevertheless, he's still worthy of consideration in the middle-to-late-middle rounds of fantasy drafts this season.

Turner's production took a small step back last season, as he finally settled in as the secondary big man on the team behind Domantas Sabonis. Turner's volume was down across the board, including his lowest scoring average since his rookie season and the lowest field goal percentage of his career. On the bright side, his 2.1 BPG was still good for fourth in the NBA and his 1.4 3PG represented a new career high.

Hachimura had a solid rookie campaign when healthy, averaging 13.5 PPG (46.6 FG%, 82.9 FT%), 6.1 RPG and 1.8 APG in 30.1 MPG. However, he missed 24 games due to injury. Hachimura plays well off the ball, which will be a key component this season, as he learns to play next to two huge scorers in the backcourt with Russell Westbrook now joining Bradley Beal. Hachimura should improve as a sophomore, and his efficiency should almost certainly increase next to a true point guard and a backcourt that draws so much defensive attention, but his volume could be limited by that same dynamic.

Wiseman currently tops the projected depth chart to be the starting center for the Warriors this season, but the No. 2 overall pick in this year's draft played only three collegiate games and is thus more raw than the veterans who typically man the middle for the Dubs. On the other hand, Wiseman is wildly talented with the length and athleticism to finish in the paint at a high clip and the defensive instincts to produce strong rebound and block numbers out the gate. The question is whether the Warriors will really give him starter's run out the gate -- if so, he could make an impact even as a rookie.

Bagley is ultra-talented and has shown brief signs of greatness at different times during his two-year career since being chosen No. 2 overall in the 2018 NBA draft. However, he has been plagued by injuries that have held him to 75 total games over those two seasons. Bagley missed the majority of last season with thumb and foot injuries but is expected to be ready for the start of this season as the starting power forward. He has been a mid-teens scorer with just under eight rebounds per game through his first two seasons, but he has some latent perimeter skills as a shooter and plenty of upside to grow into an impact player -- if he can stay healthy.

Bridges improved his counting stats as a sophomore, but his scoring efficiency dropped precipitously, and his volume per 100 possessions dropped in every category except scoring and 3-pointers. This indicates that Bridges was trying to fill a larger offensive role than he was ready for, in large part due to the dearth of scoring talent for the Hornets after Kemba Walker and Jeremy Lamb left the prior offseason. With the new additions of Gordon Hayward and LaMelo Ball, Bridges' volume could have more of a cap, but conversely, his efficiency and defensive numbers could spike as he moves back into his more comfortable role as an athletic 3-and-D producer.

Harden has consistently been the most potent offensive player in the NBA for several years, having led the NBA in scoring the past three seasons. However, Mike D'Antoni was his head coach for that entire stretch of elite play, running a variant of his potent lead-guard-centric attack. This season, D'Antoni is gone, and new coach Stephen Silas will be implementing his own offense. Will Harden receive the same primacy? Will there still be enough shots for Harden and the newly acquired John Wall to coexist in a more traditional attack? And what if Harden gets his publicly stated wish to be traded to the Nets to play with Kevin Durant and Kyrie Irving? His offense would almost have to suffer. Thus, while Harden has a strong argument to be the top fantasy pick based on his history, the questions surrounding his future make such a pick a risk.

Embiid could be the beneficiary of the offseason upheaval experienced by the 76ers this offseason. New executive Daryl Morey has already made several trades, swapping two starters in deals that brought back excellent shooters in Danny Green and Seth Curry, both of whom have averaged at least 1.7 3PG and 40.0 3FG% for their careers. They should provide more space for Embiid and Ben Simmons to work, and new coach Doc Rivers traditionally runs offensive systems where superstars are able to maximize production. Embiid has the ability to bounce back to, or even surpass, his excellent numbers from two seasons ago. If he's able to do that and stay healthy -- two big 'ifs' -- Embiid has No. 1 overall upside in fantasy.

Mitchell is coming off a strong regular-season campaign, producing similar numbers to his sophomore season. But Mitchell really took off in the playoffs, when he averaged 36.3 PPG (52.9 FG%, 94.8 FT%), 5.0 RPG, 4.9 APG, 4.7 3PG and 1.0 SPG in a seven-game classic matchup with Jamal Murray and the Nuggets. That series showed just how much upside Mitchell has in his game, and while he's not expected to approach those averages this season, he clearly has the room to dramatically increase his scoring on a regular basis should that be his focus. He should come off the board in the first few rounds of fantasy basketball drafts, and if he does make the leap that he teased in the playoffs, he has the upside to outperform his ADP.

Nurkic suffered a devastating leg injury near the end of the 2018-19 season that kept him out the entirety of the pre-bubble 2019-20 campaign, but he returned with a bang in the bubble, to the tune of 17.6 PPG (49.5 FG%, 88.6 FT%), 10.3 RPG, 4.0 APG, 2.0 BPG and 1.4 SPG during those eight contests. Nurkic is still only 26 years old, and thus still approaching his peak. He projects as one of the better centers in both points and roto leagues and is worthy of consideration in the early mid-rounds of fantasy drafts.

Middleton has been the second option for the Bucks behind Giannis Antetokounmpo for years and had settled in as a consistent 20.9 PPG player with 6.2 RPG, 4.3 APG, 2.4 3PG and 0.9 SPG. His biggest claim to fame last season was his scoring efficiency, as he flirted strongly with a 50/40/90 season by notching a 49.7 FG%, 41.5 3FG% and 91.6 FT%. Middleton will share second-option duties this season with newly acquired Jrue Holiday, but there should be enough shots that his volume won't drop very much. While conditions could be present to help his scoring efficiency, his percentages were so elevated already that it may be difficult for him to match them again. He's a solid option in the late-early rounds of fantasy drafts.

Rubio returns to where his NBA career began, having been traded back to the Timberwolves this offseason. Rubio is a known quantity at this point of his career, capable of scoring in the low teens with a handful of rebounds and just over a steal and a 3-pointer per game. Where his production fluctuates is in assists, as he averaged around nine in previous stops with the Timberwolves and Suns but only around six with the Jazz. His new role with the Timberwolves is likely more similar to what he was asked to do with the Jazz, as he'll be starting next to another lead guard in D'Angelo Russell and not on-ball as often. He's still worthy of draft consideration in the middle rounds of fantasy basketball leagues but maybe a notch down from where he would have gone had he stayed with the Suns.

Griffin played only 18 games last season before having to shut down after arthroscopic surgery on his left knee, but he was reportedly healthy enough to return if the Pistons would have been called upon to play in the bubble. Griffin, like Derrick Rose, is now an older player with a starting job on a rebuilding team. With health questions and the potential to be traded to a team that may give him a lesser role,  Griffin should slide to at least the middle rounds in most fantasy drafts. However, he still has 20-PPG upside with solid peripherals when he does play, so he probably won't fall past the later rounds.

Cousins was once a first-round fantasy pick, but he has suffered a terrible sequence of injuries, including a torn Achilles tendon, a torn quad and a torn ACL -- all in the last three years. He hasn't played since the 2018-19 season, when he played 25.7 MPG for a deep Warriors squad and averaged 16.3 PPG, 8.2 RPG, 3.6 APG, 1.5 BPG, 1.3 SPG and 0.9 3PG. With the Rockets, Cousins may cede some time to offseason acquisition Christian Wood, but there is talk that the two may be able to play together for stretches as well. Injury risk will always have to be factored in. But with all of that said, his ability to fill the stat sheet, even in part-time duty -- plus his stratospheric upside if everything breaks right -- make him worth considering in the middle/late rounds of fantasy drafts.

Gordon had a smaller role for the Magic last season, with his lowest scoring average in three seasons, but his peripheral numbers stayed consistent. He had ceded some of his role to Jonathan Isaac, but with Isaac out for the season with a knee injury, Gordon has the opportunity to bounce back in 2020-21. As such, Gordon makes for a solid middle- or late-round pick with a bit of upside in fantasy drafts.

Allen earned the larger portion of the big-man time share for the Nets last season, averaging 11.1 PPG, 9.6 RPG and 1.3 BPG in 26.5 MPG vs. DeAndre Jordan's 8.3 PPG, 10.0 RPG and 0.9 BPG in 22.0 MPG. Allen is the younger, more energetic of the two big men, and he fit in better with last season's scrappy approach. However, this season the Nets will have a more veteran team led by Kevin Durant and Kyrie Irving, two of Jordan's biggest supporters. Allen could conceivably give up a bit of primacy to a healthy Jordan but is still likely to flirt with a double-double to go with a great field goal percentage and solid defensive stats.

Sexton stepped up into his role as the leading scorer on the Cavaliers last season, averaging 20.8 PPG on a surprisingly robust 47.2 FG%. Sexton and Darius Garland are considered the backcourt of the future for the Cavaliers, both of them combo guards who can create scoring opportunities off the dribble. The Cavaliers traded their third similar guard, Jordan Clarkson, last season, which opened things up for Sexton and Garland to flourish. Expect Sexton's volume production to increase again in his third season.

White had a promising rookie season, during which he showed flashes of greatness, none more so than the last nine games, when he averaged 26.1 PPG (48.0 FG%, 90.3 FT%), 4.4 APG, 4.2 RPG and 3.9 3PG. While it would be a stretch to expect that type of production from White as a sophomore, it is clear that he has the talent and upside to produce strong enough shooter/scorer and all-around numbers to be worthy of draft attention in the middle rounds.

Barrett was the Knicks' prized rookie of the 2019 class, and he turned in decent volume at 14.3 PPG, 5.0 RPG, 2.6 APG, 1.1 3PG and 1.0 SPG. However, he absolutely struggled with his shot from every distance (40.2 FG%, 32.0 3FG% and 61.4 FT%). Barrett will be the Knicks' starting wing again this season, and the major question is whether he has improved that shot. If so, he could make a sophomore leap and become a top-100 fantasy producer. If not, his volume is still worthy of some consideration in points leagues, but he would be difficult to use in roto/categories formats.

Durant is back, and ready to try again to stake his claim as the best player in the NBA. However, those goals are tied more to the Nets winning than to fantasy basketball production. Durant will have to mesh with high-volume Kyrie Irving while joining a Nets team that had been good enough to make the playoffs last season, and that could cut a bit into his volume. He is also returning from a devastating Achilles tendon rupture, though early indications are that he appears to be fully recovered.

Tatum made multiple leaps last season, assuming the role of team leader early before developing into an All-NBA caliber player during the second half of the season. Tatum upped his numbers to 26.6 PPG (48.4 FG%, 77.2 FT%), 7.0 RPG, 3.6 3PG, 3.3 APG, 1.5 SPG and 0.9 BPG during the last 30 games of the regular season. He then maintained or increased that volume during 17 playoff games. Tatum is still only 22 years old and looks poised to make another leap to potential MVP candidate as soon as this season, as an elite shooter/scorer and all-around producer who is the unquestioned team leader of a Celtics squad expected to contend.

Gilgeous-Alexander seems ready to make the leap. He had a solid rookie season with the Clippers, then an excellent sophomore campaign with the Thunder, as one of their triumvirate of impact guards. This season, with Chris Paul and Dennis Schroder on new teams, Gilgeous-Alexander is the only offensive engine left. Teammates like Al Horford, Trevor Ariza and George Hill will lend the Thunder a veteran presence, but the Thunder are purely in rebuild mode and Gilgeous-Alexander is the centerpiece. It would be surprising if he didn't average well over 20 points with at least five rebounds and five assists, making him worthy of a pick in the early rounds of fantasy drafts.

Siakam took the superstar leap last season, stepping into the scoring void left by Kawhi Leonard's departure to increase his average by six full points up to 22.9 PPG. A large part of that point increase came from behind the arc, where he increased from 1.0 to 2.2 3PG. Siakam's perimeter offense and ability to score off the dribble were still a work in progress, and he still has room to improve them this season. He remained a strong defender and passer, with scoring efficiency being the only area where he regressed, which made sense, as he became the focal point of opposing defenses instead of getting to play off another transcendent star. Siakam is a borderline-first-round fantasy talent this season, though he is likely to have a second-round ADP.

Fox has improved by leaps and bounds each season of his young career thus far. Last season, he reached new high marks of 21.1 PPG on 48.0 FG%, and he rounded out his efforts with 6.8 APG, 3.8 RPG, 1.5 SPG, 1.1 3PG and 0.5 BPG. Fox is the clear face of the Kings and should continue to improve in Season 4. He's worthy of consideration in the late-early rounds of fantasy drafts and has the upside to make another leap toward the elite this season.

Porzingis returned from a torn ACL last season and flirted with his first 20-10 season, grabbing a career-best 9.5 rebounds per game with 20.4 points. Like Doncic, he stepped up his production even more once he entered the bubble, averaging 30.5 PPG in six regular season games before injury cut his playoffs short. Injuries are, as ever, the biggest question mark for Porzingis this season. He will miss the start of the season as he recovers from right knee surgery for a torn meniscus, then he will have to play himself back into shape during the season. If he's able to stay healthy, he has shown that he is an elite producer in this system ... if.

Capela was an easy top-50 fantasy producer during his last years as a Rocket, but his role for the Hawks is a bit murkier. In today's spread-out-and-shoot NBA, the Hawks could be set to run more action with John Collins and Danilo Gallinari as the big men with Capela on the bench. When Capela does play, he should be strong on the glass and as a defender, and he should also be a high-efficiency finisher in the pick-and-roll playing off Trae Young.

Ball quietly had his best production as a pro last season, driven largely by a much improved 3-point shot that allowed him to make a career-best 2.3 3PG on 37.5 3FG% and increase his scoring average to 11.8 PPG. Ball spent last season playing next to an elite lead guard in Jrue Holiday, splitting duties running the offense and setting up off the ball for spot-up 3-pointers. He'll likely have a similar role this season next to Eric Bledsoe, and at only 23 years old, he should still be getting better. With his strong assists (7.0 APG), rebounds (6.1 RPG) and defensive stats (1.4 SPG, 0.6 BPG), Ball has the all-around game to excel in both points and roto leagues.

Herro had a solid rookie season on the whole, but it was his time in the bubble -- and his in-game snarl that went viral on memes worldwide -- that made him a star. Herro averaged 21.6 PPG, 4.8 RPG, 4.4 APG and 2.2 3PG during the past five regular seasons in the bubble, then followed that up with a memorable playoffs run that reached a high-water mark of 37 points, 6 rebounds, 5 3-pointers and 3 assists in a crucial win over the Celtics in the Eastern Conference Finals. Herro is expected to continue to come off the bench as a sophomore, but he should get close to starter's minutes and is worthy of consideration in the middle rounds of fantasy basketball drafts.

Graham burst onto the scene in a major way last season, surprisingly snatching the mantle as the primary offensive engine for the Hornets to the tune of 18.2 PPG, 7.5 APG and 3.5 3PG. The expectation had been that newcomer Terry Rozier would run the show, but Graham outpaced him in every major offensive category. The new challenges this season will come from LaMelo Ball -- the No. 3 overall draft pick, whom many expect to come in and be the new face of the Hornets -- and free-agent acquisition Gordon Hayward. But while Ball may encroach on Graham's floor-general primacy and Hayward on his scoring volume, Graham should still be an offensive leader and has some upside to improve his scoring efficiency next to other offensive threats who can generate more open shots.

Williams' scoring average dropped slightly last season, as expected, after the Clippers brought in two high-volume scorers in Kawhi Leonard and Paul George. However, his 18.2 PPG was still the third-highest mark of his career, and he bolstered that with career highs of 5.6 APG and 3.1 RPG. Williams will once again be a Sixth Man of the Year favorite going into this season, as he maintains a similar role to the one he's filled since joining the Clippers three seasons ago.

Toppin is the most polished, productive member of this season's rookie class. The reigning AP collegiate player of the year had a 64.7 FG% last season, the third best of all-time among winners of that award, behind only Bill Walton (1971-74) and Zion Williamson (2018-19) -- and ahead of Lew Alcindor (Kareem Abdul-Jabbar). Williamson, of course, went on to shoot an elite 58.3 FG% as a rookie which bodes well for Toppin's prospects. Toppin is a combo forward, who has strong post moves, a nice face-up game and a reliable mid-range jumper with the potential to develop 3-point range. He is also a high flyer, which should let him finish around the rim. He's one of the safest bets in this rookie class, worthy of draft consideration in the middle to late rounds.

Dinwiddie developed into the leading offensive engine on the Nets last season, averaging career bests of 20.6 PPG, 6.8 APG and 1.9 3PG in 31.2 MPG in a starting role once Kyrie Irving was injured. With Irving and Kevin Durant returning to take the mantle this season, Dinwiddie is likely to settle back into a super-sixth-man role similar to those recently helmed elsewhere by Lou Williams and Dennis Schroder. Dinwiddie's volume as a scorer and distributor should decrease, but he can still produce fantasy-worthy numbers and get close to 30 MPG, if he can comfortably mesh his efforts as the leading offense generator of the second unit and a contributing cog next to the stars in the half-closing units.

Bryant has gotten better in each of his three NBA seasons thus far, and he finished the 2019-20 season with a bang that indicates he could be ready to step forward again this season. Bryant was borderline dominant in the bubble, averaging 18.6 PPG (53.2 FG%, 76.2 FT%), 8.9 RPG, 2.0 BPG, 1.9 3PG, 1.5 APG and 1.4 SPG in 30.8 MPG over those eight contests. Bryant enters this season as the clear starter at center for the Wizards, with journeyman Robin Lopez in town purely as a backup, though Davis Bertans could get some minutes as a small-ball 5. Playing off the new dynamic backcourt of Russell Westbrook and Bradley Beal could generate more open looks for Bryant this season.

Towns had the best per-game averages of his career last season, with career-best marks of 26.5 PPG, 4.4 APG, 3.3 3PG and 0.9 SPG to go with elite scoring efficiency and strong blocks. However, for the first time in his career, Towns missed significant time due to a knee injury and, later, a wrist issue that ultimately ended his season. If Towns is fully healthy this season, he has a legitimate claim for the top pick in either points or roto leagues as a player with excellent volume and no real weakness.

Curry has the potential to be the best in the league on a per-game basis, but there are legitimate concerns that it may be too hard on him physically to actually do it. For the second season in a row, Curry will be without his injured Splash Brother Klay Thompson, and he will thus be relied upon to carry the offense. Last season, under these circumstances, Curry suffered a catastrophic wrist injury in the fourth game and was able to return for only one more game before the league shut down. This season, Curry has better finishers around him with Kelly Oubre Jr. and Andrew Wiggins on the wings instead of a co-creator like D'Angelo Russell, which bodes well for Curry's offense creation this season -- as long as he's able to stay healthy.

Collins improved again in his third year, becoming a legit 20-10 big man with averages of 21.6 PPG and 11.2 RPG and career highs in field goal percentage (58.3 FG%), free throw percentage (80.0 FT%) and blocks (1.6 BPG). On the downside, he played only 41 games last season, has an uncertain contract extension situation, and the Hawks just traded for Danilo Gallinari and gave him more than $60M to "back up" Collins. Collins can produce if he gets the minutes for the Hawks, but there are enough question marks to give some pause.

Vucevic turned in a second consecutive stellar and healthy season to cement himself among the top centers in the league. He's a 20-10 threat every night, and well-rounded enough to dish almost four assists per game. For roto purposes, he also contributes to the three most challenging stats to acquire, with three-year averages of 1.2 3PG, 1.0 SPG and 1.0 BPG. He provides solid value in the third or fourth round of fantasy drafts.

McCollum is coming off an excellent campaign, including career-best marks of 2.8 3PG, 4.4 APG, 4.2 RPG and 0.6 BPG to support his typically strong 22.2 PPG as the No. 2 scorer on the Trail Blazers, supporting Damian Lillard. The Trail Blazers appear to be stronger this season, with center Jusuf Nurkic healthy, new addition Robert Covington to provide volume 3-point shooting from the frontcourt, and Carmelo Anthony signed and in the fold to start the season. While these players could potentially eat into McCollum's shots, they should also open up the floor for him to score more efficiently and potentially improve further in assists. He's a solid early/mid-round prospect in fantasy drafts.

Hayward quietly had a solid bounce-back campaign for the Celtics last season, posting a career-best 6.7 RPG, a five-season-best 4.1 APG, and his highest scoring average since leaving the Jazz. However, he continued to battle health issues in his second season following his gruesome ankle injury, and his team role was limited by the outstanding wing talent that surrounded him. That shouldn't be the case with the Hornets, where he is clearly the most talented forward on the team and will be relied upon as a primary scorer and do-everything wing. If healthy, Hayward has the opportunity to return to the numbers that made him an All-Star for the Jazz.

Brown had a much larger role last season with Kyrie Irving, Terry Rozier and Marcus Morris all moving on and opening up space for him. He took advantage with a career-best season, averaging 20.3 PPG, 6.4 RPG and 2.3 3PG in 33.9 MPG. Having turned 24 years old in October, Brown could be in for another leap this season with Gordon Hayward having moved on to officially cede Brown and Jayson Tatum the reigns as the star wings on the Celtics.

Murray is coming off his best season, averaging 10.9 PPG (46.2 FG%, 79.8 FT%), 5.8 RPG, 4.1 APG, 1.7 SPG and 0.6 3PG -- all career highs. Murray just turned 24 years old and is clearly improving. He has the potential to make a leap to a borderline impact player this season as part of the Spurs' young backcourt that also features Derrick White. That potential makes him worthy of consideration in the middle rounds of fantasy drafts as a solid upside pick.

Markkanen took a surprising step backwards last season, offering career lows in points, rebounds, blocks, field goal percentage and free throw percentage in his third campaign. Some of his struggles seemed due to injury, a consistent issue throughout his career, as he's missed at least 14 games every season. Markkanen is the most talented scorer in the Bulls' frontcourt, and the lane is still open for him to produce, as he has little competition in that role for a talent-bereft Bulls squad.

Smart came into his own last season, averaging career highs of 12.9 PPG, 4.9 APG and 2.3 3PG in his role as the starting shooting guard. He improved on those numbers in the playoffs (14.5 PPG, 5.2 RPG, 4.6 APG and 2.4 3PG) to indicate that he still has some untapped potential. Smart is known more for his defense than his offense and is a plus source of both steals and 3-pointers in addition to solid all-around counting stats in his unique team role.

Clarke had an impressive rookie season with excellent per-minute numbers, translating to per 36-minute averages of 19.4 PP36 (61.8 FG%, 75.9 FT%), 9.6 RP36, 2.2 AP36, 1.3 BP36, 0.9 SP36 and 0.6 3P36. This is particularly relevant to start the season, when Clarke could be in line to start at power forward while Jaren Jackson Jr. is recovering from August knee surgery. Jackson is expected back early in the season, but if Clarke does get starter's minutes to begin the season, he could put some nice numbers on the board.

Washington had a strong rookie season, good enough to be named to the second team of the All-Rookie squad. He proved himself capable of plus scoring and shooting from the power forward position, and showed the potential to soon join the select club of players capable of averaging at least one block, steal and 3-pointer per game. Washington should improve as a sophomore, especially with more room to operate alongside more talented teammates and a better point guard (LaMelo Ball) capable of creating easier scoring opportunities for him.

The Timberwolves made Edwards the No. 1 overall pick in this year's NBA Draft, signaling their faith in his ability to develop into their third star to mesh with Karl-Anthony Towns and D'Angelo Russell. Edwards is 6-foot-5 but has long arms and is built like a tank, so he projects as their starting small forward. He's an athletic finisher in the open court and was a volume shooter/scorer at low efficiency in college, but his size and athleticism could allow him to take advantage of more open driving lanes in the pros and finish more at the rim. He projects as a plus scorer as a rookie, likely with solid peripheral contributions in rebounds, steals and 3-pointers. He's worthy of draft consideration in the middle-to-late-middle rounds of fantasy basketball drafts.

Doncic posted MVP-caliber numbers as a sophomore, then somehow stepped it up once the action moved to the bubble -- to the point that he nearly averaged a 30-10-10 triple-double during the seven regular-season games and six playoffs contests. Doncic can shoot from everywhere, has the best step-back 3-pointer this side of James Harden, is an excellent passer and has the size to dominate the glass and finish at the rim. His game has no weakness, and he has a legitimate chance to generate NBA-best fantasy production in his third season.

Booker has turned in consecutive seasons averaging almost the exact same volume, with a two-year average of 26.6 PPG, 6.6 APG, 4.2 RPG, 2.1 3PG and 0.8 SPG. The difference is that last season, Booker became more efficient as a scorer, raising all three shooting percentages over the previous season, up to 48.9 FG%, 35.4 3FG% and 91.9 FT%. He has done more team offense generation during those two seasons, and it will be interesting to see if that continues with Chris Paul now in town to run the show. Paul could help Booker's efficiency to increase yet again, as he should get the ball in his favorite spots to shoot at a rate he's never had before. Booker very well could produce at a first-round fantasy level this season.

Butler is coming off one of the most memorable seasons of his career, punctuated by leading the hungry underdog Heat to the NBA Finals. While this wasn't his most impressive scoring season, he was still a 19.9 PPG scorer on solid field goal percentages, and he set new career highs with 6.7 RPG, 6.0 APG and 9.1 FTA at a solid 83.4 FT%. His all-around production makes Butler worthy of consideration as early as the second round of fantasy basketball drafts.

Wood is a 6-foot-10, athletic power forward who had never played more than 21 games in any of his first three seasons in the NBA before getting the chance to shine with the Pistons. He was solid as a backup during his first 48 games of the season, but when Andre Drummond was traded and Blake Griffin was injured, Wood was called on to start down the stretch. He took full advantage of the opportunity, igniting to the tune of 22.6 PPG (55.8 FG%, 76.5 FT%), 9.8 RPG, 1.6 3PG, 0.9 BPG and 0.9 SPG during his last 14 games. This offseason, Wood signed with the Rockets, presumably as a starter, as they end their small-ball experiment from last season. Wood will likely take a volume hit on a team with both James Harden and John Wall, but otherwise has the opportunity to break out in his first full season as an expected impact player.

DeRozan is a production metronome. His counting averages last season (22.1 PPG, 5.6 APG, 5.5 RPG, 1.0 SPG, 0.3 BPG, 0.1 3PG) are eerily similar to his three-year averages  (22.1 PPG, 5.7 APG, 5.1 RPG, 1.1 SPG, 0.3 BPG, 0.5 3PG). That includes his last season with the Raptors and first two with the Spurs, so it doesn't seem to matter for which team he plays. You know what you're going to get from him, and it translates to consideration in the third or fourth round in most fantasy basketball drafts.

Aldridge's scoring volume has decreased in each of the past two seasons, coinciding with the Spurs bringing DeMar DeRozan to town and making him their top scoring option. Last season, Aldridge's production also declined in rebounds, though he made up for that with a slight bump in steals and career highs of 1.6 BPG and 1.2 3PG. Aldridge's season ended early due to a shoulder injury, but he is expected to be close to full strength by the time the season starts. Aldridge is also expected to shoot even more 3-pointers this season, which makes sense, since he is 35 years old and the NBA game has shifted more to the perimeter.

Love is coming off his healthiest campaign since 2015-16, having missed only nine games last season. He characteristically flirted with a 20-10 season, though he fell short of those marks for the sixth season in a row. Love did make a career-best 2.6 3-pointers per game, and his 3.2 APG were his most in six seasons as well. He is no longer a potential franchise player, but when healthy, he can still generate upper-round fantasy production.

Bertans had a breakout campaign in 2019-20, parlaying a sixth-man role on the Wizards into career-best marks of 15.4 PPG, 4.5 RPG and 3.7 3PG on 42.4 3FG% in 29.3 MPG. That 3-point shot from a 6-foot-10 forward made Bertans one of the best floor-spacers in the league, and the Wizards rewarded him this offseason with a five-year, $80M contract. Bertans should reprise his role again this season and could actually get more open looks with Russell Westbrook and Bradley Beal drawing most of the attention of opposing defenses.

Curry averaged 12.4 PPG and 2.3 3PG in a sixth-man role for the Mavericks last season, and he may have a slightly larger role as the long-term successor to J.J. Redick for the 76ers. He is unlikely to produce enough volume to be draft-worthy in points leagues, but his volume 3-point shooting puts him on the radar in late rounds of roto leagues.

Anunoby is a big defensive wing who is developing more offensive polish as his career progresses. His production has improved each season of his career, and this season, he has the upside to grow into a scorer in the low-teens with solid rebounding, defensive numbers and 3-pointers in his ledger. He may be worth a look in the late rounds of fantasy basketball drafts.

Ibaka followed former Raptors teammate Kawhi Leonard to the Clippers this offseason, filling the minutes and role of the departed Montrezl Harrell. Ibaka should therefore be able to get his typical fill of shots and opportunities to build on the career-high 15.4 PPG and 8.2 RPG he produced a season ago. He is worthy of fantasy consideration in the mid-to-late portion of drafts.

Rose enters the season at the top of the depth chart for a Pistons team that seems well on its way to a youth movement rebuild. Rose averaged 18.1 PPG and 5.6 APG last season, his best performance in both categories since before his disastrous knee injury in 2012. He missed 16 games last season, his ninth straight season missing at least that many games, and the 32-year-old is also risky because the Pistons could trade him to a contending team that wouldn't have as big of a role for him.

Baynes is a breakout candidate this season after joining the Raptors, sporting the opportunity to play a larger role in the absence of Marc Gasol and Serge Ibaka. Baynes took a step forward last season when given a larger opportunity for the Suns and produced per-36-minute numbers of 18.5 PP36 (48.0 FG%, 74.7 FT%), 9.1 RP36, 2.6 AP36 and 2.3 3P36. If Baynes gets near 30 minutes per game, that type of production would be at the high end --but not far outside of reasonable expectations as a best-case scenario.

Gordon battled injuries most of last season, when he played only 36 games. When he returned, he initially fought major rust, as he attempted to settle in as the third scoring option behind usage monsters James Harden and Russell Westbrook. The break in the season allowed Gordon some extra time to heal, and during the playoffs, he returned to form, averaging 18.5 PPG, 3.2 APG, 2.7 RPG and 2.5 3PG during the first 11 games of the postseason. There are questions for the Rockets heading into the season, with a new front office philosophy and head coach, in addition to trade rumors swirling around Harden and Westbrook. However, one thing that's known is that Gordon is a professional scorer, and if he's healthy and getting normal usage, he should score in the mid-to-upper teens with good 3-point shooting. He is worthy of some consideration late in fantasy drafts.

Davis posted elite production across the board last season, contributing positively to every fantasy category with large-volume stats, high shooting efficiency and the unique status as the only player in the NBA to average more than two blocks (2.3 BPG), 1.5 steals and more than a 3-pointer (1.2 3PG). He was also relatively durable, missing only nine games to mark his third season out of the past four with fewer than 10 missed games. Davis is 27 years old, at his peak, and could look to carry a slightly larger role this season to take some regular-season pressure off his older MVP teammate LeBron James. Outside of potential lingering durability questions and the slight volume cap he endures/enjoys while playing with another elite producer in James, Davis otherwise has a solid argument as a potential top overall fantasy draft pick candidate this season.

Ayton has been overshadowed by draft-mates Luka Doncic and Trae Young, but he has quietly produced borderline dominant numbers as a young center. He averaged 18.2 PPG (54.6 FG%, 75.3 FT%) with 11.5 RPG, 1.9 APG, 1.5 BPG and 0.7 SPG as a sophomore, but his scoring volume and efficiency could very well increase this season while playing off elite point guard Chris Paul. Ayton has clear 20-10 potential with strong peripherals and could actually be undervalued, if he makes it to the third round of fantasy basketball drafts.

Adebayo entered last season as a likely breakout candidate after Hassan Whiteside moved on to the Trail Blazers, and he more than fulfilled that promise with an explosive campaign, during which he demonstrated strong, high-efficiency scoring with excellent rebounding, great passing from a big man and more than a block and steal per game. Adebayo is expected to continue to improve, and it is very reasonable that he might outplay his third-round grade in fantasy drafts and produce an elite season.

Paul had an outstanding campaign with the Thunder last season, bouncing back from a down season with the Rockets the season prior and re-establishing himself as arguably the best pure point guard in the NBA. He joins a young, talented Suns squad this season with the potential to be the catalyst that pushes them into contention. For Paul, his assists and scoring efficiency should be excellent when surrounded by finishers of the caliber of Devin Booker and Deandre Ayton. The main questions are age and durability, as he had missed at least 21 games in each of the three campaigns before last season.

VanVleet made the leap from a sixth man to a core starter for the Raptors last season, smashing career bests in every category to the tune of 17.6 PPG, 6.6 APG, 3.8 RPG, 2.7 3PG and 1.9 SPG. VanVleet's ability to create offense off the dribble for himself and his teammates meshed perfectly with backcourt mate Kyle Lowry, with each taking turns as the floor general and off-ball finisher to set the table for the team. VanVleet earned a huge contract this offseason and is poised to improve even more this campaign, as he continues to grow into his role.

Valanciunas is one of the most efficient, effective "true" centers in the NBA. Valanciunas operates around the rim at both ends, averages a solid points-rebounds double-double and has produced field goal percentages as high as last season's 58.5 FG%.  And while his free throw percentage slipped a bit last season, his average in the three seasons prior was 80.4 FT%.  Valunciunas has averaged about 10 missed games per season for the past several years, giving him a reasonably durable record that supports his grade as an early-middle-round fantasy draft prospect.

Warren averaged 18.9 PPG (49.3 FG%, 77.6 FT%) with 4.7 RPG, 1.1 SPG and 0.6 BPG during his last two seasons with the Suns, and he matched those numbers almost verbatim during his first 61 games with the Pacers to the tune of 18.7 PPG (52.9 FG%, 81.2 FT%), 4.0 RPG, 1.1 SPG and 0.4 BPG. However, Warren ignited during his seven regular-season games in the bubble, averaging 31.0 PPG (57.8 FG%, 88.9 FT%), 6.3 RPG, 1.3 SPG and 1.2 BPG. Now, some of that may have been a hot streak -- and the rebounding elevation was clearly due in part to the injury absence of leading rebounder Domantas Sabonis. However, there are reasons for optimism. Warren should be peaking at 27 years old, and he has demonstrated elite 3-point shooting for two seasons in a row now. Plus, the Pacers' lack of an elite scorer limited their upside last season, so Warren should get the green light if he shows any signs of being able to take up that mantle.

LeVert stepped forward as one of the best players on the Nets with Kevin Durant and Kyrie Irving out last season, and he has the chance to settle in as the third cog for the new-look Nets. LeVert averaged 18.7 PPG with 4.4 APG, 4.2 RPG, 1.8 3PG and 1.2 SPG last season, but his scoring volume will almost certainly decrease next to Durant and Irving. However, LeVert should improve his efficiency and perhaps his volume as a 3-point shooter with open looks created by defenses focusing on his superstar teammates.

Robinson is one of the greatest shooters in the NBA and last season made 3.7 3PG at a whopping 44.6 3FG%. He averaged in the low teens for points with a few rebounds and excellent shooting percentages, but Robinson's most marketable skill is his 3-point shooting. It gives him clear value in roto leagues and makes him worthy of at least some late-round consideration in the last rounds of deep points-based leagues.

Walker stepped back his volume in his first season with the Celtics, producing his lowest scoring and assist numbers in five seasons. He also dealt with a nagging knee injury that visibly slowed him at times last season, which seemingly opened the door for Jayson Tatum and Jaylen Brown to step forward with the best numbers of their young careers. Walker's knee still isn't right, and he'll miss the start of the season due to a procedure on the joint. When he does play, Walker likely will continue in a more tertiary role for the Celtics, as Tatum and Brown consolidate as the focal scorers on this team. Walker may still flirt with 20 PPG and 5 APG, but his days of 25 and 6 are seemingly behind him.

Fournier is coming off his best scoring season, posting career-highs of 18.5 PPG and 2.6 3PG. The Magic return the same backcourt as last season, so his role and production should remain relatively similar for this campaign. Fournier is a solid pick in late rounds of fantasy drafts.

Bridges came on strongly as last season progressed, finishing with a 13-game stretch averaging 13.5 PPG (50.8 FG%, 87.5 FT%), 4.5 RPG, 2.2 APG, 1.9 3PG, 0.9 SPG and 0.8 BPG. Bridges is a strong 3-and-D wing with the athleticism to finish at the rim, so he should benefit from the presence of an elite point guard like Chris Paul setting the table for the team. He is worthy of fantasy draft consideration in the late rounds, with enough upside to justify selection in the middle rounds of roto leagues.

Porter entered the bubble last season at the tail end of an unremarkable rookie campaign, still recovering from the injuries that had forced him to sit out the entirety of his first season. Everything changed in the bubble, though, as injuries gave Porter the opportunity to start during a stretch when Jamal Murray was also sidelined. Porter took advantage, averaging 22.0 PPG (55.1 FG%, 93.1 FT%), 8.6 RPG, 2.7 3PG, 1.0 SPG and 0.9 BPG in 33.3 MPG over seven regular season bubble games. Porter slowed down once Murray returned and the playoffs began, but he enters his sophomore season with a distinct opportunity to become an impact player worthy of mid-round fantasy consideration.

James won his fourth Finals MVP in mid-October, capping an extra 21 games of playoffs action after having played in 67 of 71 Lakers regular-season games. James will turn 36 years old about a week into what will be his 18th NBA season. He has been publicly adamant in the past about not load managing, but this high concentration of games in such close temporal proximity at this age has to put a strain on even an all-timer like James. The questions about James' availability for this season, either due to load management or increased risk of injury, are some of the only arguments against him being the potential top pick in fantasy drafts this season. Otherwise, he is fresh off the first 25-10 season of his illustrious career, is the defending assists leader in the NBA, made a career-best 2.2 3PG last season, and looks poised for across-the-board excellence -- outside of free throw percentage -- for the 18th straight season.

Leonard's first season with the Clippers resulted in some of the best numbers of his career, as he set new high marks with 27.1 PPG, 4.9 APG and 2.2 3PG. He still missed 15 games due to injury and load management, but that is expected at this point and baked into his value. He carried a bit heavier load than expected with Paul George struggling with his own injuries, and it's possible that Leonard takes a slight step backward this season with George healthy -- but not much of one, because Leonard is one of the most consistent players in the league and still at the top of his game. He is a first-round fantasy talent, but with the expected missed games, he drops a round or two in overall value.

Morant was everything advertised and more in an electric first season that resulted in him winning Rookie of the Year. It's easy to focus on his highlight dunks and slick dribbling, but what shows up in the numbers is how excellent he is at creating offense for himself and teammates. Morant had strong averages of 17.8 PPG and 7.3 APG for the season, but in the bubble, he gave a preview of what's to come with averages of 19.0 PPG and 9.9 APG in those eight games. He projects to improve even more as a sophomore, enough that he could very reasonably outperform his current late third-round grade in fantasy drafts.

Whiteside had one of the best campaigns of his career last season, manning the middle for the Trail Blazers with Jusuf Nurkic sidelined. He led the NBA with 2.9 BPG, averaged a strong 15.5 PPG-13.5 RPG double-double and shot 62.1 percent from the field. This season, Whiteside joins the Kings on a one-year deal, presumably battling with Richaun Holmes for the starting spot. While this may prevent Whiteside from averaging the 30.0 MPG that he did a season ago, he has such strong per-minute rates that he would still be worthy of fantasy draft consideration in the middle rounds even if he plays only half the center minutes for the Kings this season.

LaVine is coming off another career season, having set personal bests with 25.5 PPG, 4.8 RPG and 3.1 3PG. He also had his healthiest season since 2015-16, missing only seven games before the season was shut down. LaVine is still only 25 years old, ramping up toward his peak, so if he's able to stay on the court again this season, he should be in for another big campaign.

Robinson has been a per-minute monster since entering the NBA, with per-36 minute averages of 15.0 PP36, (NBA league-leading) 74.2 FG%, 56.8 FT%, 10.9 RP36, 3.0 BP36 and 1.3 3P36 last season. Unfortunately, he also averaged 4.9 fouls per 36, which is part of what has limited his ability to actually play that many minutes per game. Robinson is expected to move into the starting lineup for the Knicks this season, and if he can stay on the court, he projects to produce a solid double-double with great defensive stats. This makes him worthy of consideration by the late-early/early-middle rounds of fantasy basketball drafts.

Horford is coming off a campaign, during which he had to play out of position at power forward to try to fit in on a mismatched 76ers lineup. Moving to a more perimeter role to get out of Joel Embiid's way negatively affected his ability to block shots on defense and also lowered his field goal percentage and, thus, his scoring potential. On the other hand, he set a new career high with 1.5 3-pointers per game. His rebounding, steals and assists remained similar to his last season with the Celtics. He's now in a new environment, on a talent-bereft Thunder squad with whom he'll be the primary big man. It's a rebuilding squad, and Horford is 34 years old, so he may not pull major minutes, but he has the opportunity to do at the 5 what Chris Paul did last season at the point: show he still has it and make the best of the rebuild. Unless the Thunder trade him again, expect his numbers to return to at least where they were with the Celtics, making him a viable mid-round pick with upside.

Haliburton has been tabbed by many as the potential steal of this draft. A long point guard who makes good decisions but can also operate off the ball, he is expected to be able to play with De'Aaron Fox and also lead the second unit. Given Buddy Hield's public issues with coach Luke Walton, it's possible that Haliburton could earn the starting shooting guard job this season. Even if he doesn't, and is instead a sixth man, he's got a high floor for a rookie and enough upside to be worth a flyer late in drafts.

Plumlee backed up Nikola Jokic for the past four seasons with the Nuggets, but he joins the Pistons as their presumptive starting center. Plumlee started 17 games during the 2018-19 season and flirted with a double-double with 10.5 PPG, 8.0 RPG, 3.5 APG, 1.2 BPG and 1.0 SPG. He could replicate that level of production as a starter on the Pistons, making him worthy of late-round consideration.

Wright joined the Pistons during the offseason and may enter the season as their starting shooting guard. Wright averaged 14.5 PPG, 7.4 RPG, 7.2 APG and 1.7 SPG in 13 games as a starter for the Grizzlies during the 2018-19 season, showing his upside on a team that gives him plenty of minutes and responsibility. That level of all-around production is beyond expectation, but he is at least worthy of late-round consideration as an upside play for his new team.

DeVincenzo was very nearly traded during the offseason as part of a deal to bring Bogdan Bogdanovic to the Bucks, but when that deal fell through, DiVincenzo emerged as the likely starter at shooting guard for the Bucks this season. DiVincenzo's per-36 numbers last season were 14.4 PPG, 7.5 RPG, 3.6 APG, 2.0 SPG and 2.0 3PG. While he won't get quite that many minutes, and his pace would likely be lessened against starting competition, he appears poised to be a low-double-digit scorer with solid peripheral numbers, especially in steals and 3-pointers. He is worth considering in later rounds of fantasy drafts.

Zubac showed occasional flashes of greatness last season, but despite starting, he played only 18.4 MPG and took a back seat to Sixth Man of the Year Montrezl Harrell. Harrell moved across the hall to the Lakers, but he was replaced by new signee Serge Ibaka to keep Zubac as the secondary big man on the team. Zubac is still only 23 years old and has low double-double potential, if he were to play more minutes, but barring injury, he is likely not worthy of draft consideration in most fantasy leagues.

Lillard turned in the best production of his career last season, averaging personal bests of 30.0 PPG, 46.3 FG%, 8.0 APG and 4.1 3PG as one of the top offensive players in the league. Those numbers spiked in the bubble, where he turned in 37.6 PPG (49.7 FG%, 88.8 FT%), 9.6 APG, 5.5 3PG, 4.3 RPG and 1.4 SPG in eight contests to will the Trail Blazers into the postseason. Lillard is set up to have another outstanding effort this season, with a healthy Jusuf Nurkic and an elite stretch-4 in Robert Covington to open up the floor to let him work. Lillard carries a clear first-round grade in both points and roto drafts.

Drummond was traded to the Cavaliers during last season, and that gives him his first real question marks in years. Drummond averaged 17.5 PPG during his eight games with the Cavaliers last season, almost exactly the same as his last three seasons with the Pistons, but his rebounding dropped to only 11.1 RPG after routinely averaging at least 15 RPG for Detroit. On the bright side, Drummond played limited minutes during his short stint with the Pistons, and with Tristan Thompson gone and replaced by role player JaVale McGee, Drummond should get the minutes to return to his usual production levels this season.

Last season, George battled through recovery from preseason surgery on both shoulders and a January hamstring injury to ultimately post his lowest numbers in half a decade. He played only 29.6 MPG, down seven minutes from the previous season, and saw his stats fall across the board, as he settled in as a clear secondary option for the Clippers behind Kawhi Leonard. George should be healthier to start this season, and he'll be playing for new coach Tyronn Lue instead of Doc Rivers, so he could bounce back closer to his normal minutes and role. As such, he still has second-round fantasy draft upside, even if he carries a third-round grade.

Holiday had flourished with the Pelicans, with three-year averages of 19.7 PPG, 6.8 APG, 4.7 RPG, 1.7 3PG, 1.6 SPG and 0.8 BPG. He is a strong offense creator for himself and teammates, a high-efficiency perimeter finisher with shooting range, and an excellent perimeter defender as well. He brings these to the table in a new situation with the Bucks, where he will get to play off Giannis Antetokounmpo on both sides of the ball. His scoring volume could drop slightly, but his scoring efficiency and assist opportunities could rise, and, since he has more license to take risks on defense with the Defensive Player of the Year alongside him, his steals could increase as well.

Russell is a shooter/scorer lead guard whose production has stayed pretty similar during the past two seasons, when he played for three different teams and averaged 21.8 PPG (43.1 FG%, 79.5 FT%), 6.7 APG, 3.9 RPG, 3.1 3PG and 1.2 SPG. He was traded to the Timberwolves last season to be the star second option to Karl-Anthony Towns, but injuries prevented them from getting much run together. The Timberwolves have added No. 1 overall pick Anthony Edwards and starting point guard Ricky Rubio this offseason, which means that Russell will likely play more off the ball as a finisher and relatively less as a creator this season. Nevertheless, his production and potential make him worthy of fantasy basketball consideration in the late-early rounds of fantasy drafts.

Oubre broke out as an off-ball scoring option with the Suns during the past two seasons, and he seems like an ideal fit in the shooting guard mold for the Warriors' system. He averaged 18.7 PPG and 1.9 3PG on 35.2 3FG%, but 95.4% of his 3-point attempts were assisted (according to Basketball Reference). In the Warriors' offense, Stephen Curry and Draymond Green will be responsible for creating open looks that Oubre will be tasked with knocking down. Oubre also inherits Klay Thompson's defensive role as the primary wing defender, and defensively, he has averaged just over a steal and just under a block in each of the past two seasons.

Schroder shined as a sixth man with the Thunder last season, turning in career highs of 46.9 FG%, 1.9 3PG and 38.5 3FG% in addition to the second-best scoring volume of his career at 18.9 PPG. This season, he joins the Lakers and will play off another legendary playmaker in LeBron James after teaming with Chris Paul last season. Schroder should post similar numbers overall and may have slightly more assist potential for the Lakers than he did as one of three point guards leading the Thunder attack a season ago. He's worthy of consideration in the early middle rounds of fantasy basketball drafts.

Gallinari has turned in two straight relatively healthy seasons after battling injuries for the first decade of his career, averaging a strong 19.3 PPG, 5.7 RPG, 2.6 3PG and 2.3 APG in 29.9 MPG for two different teams during that stretch. He now joins an up-and-coming Hawks offense that should allow him to get plenty of good looks. He was nominally brought in to back up John Collins, but there should be space for him to get his 30ish minutes and solid production, as long as he can stay healthy.

Richardson battled injuries and a poor fit with the 76ers last season, which resulted in a drop in scoring, assists, rebounds, 3-pointers and steals from the season before with the Heat. Richardson now has a new opportunity with a Mavericks team that seemingly fits his skill set much better. Instead of having to be the floor-spacer, he'll be one of several shooters on the court at any given time and playing next to one of the most gifted offensive creators of this generation (Doncic). Richardson is more jack-of-all-trades than an impact offensive player, but he has upside to score in the mid-teens with multiple treys and solid peripheral numbers this season.

Gasol's NBA career will wind down where it almost began, as the Lakers once had him under contract prior to his rookie season before ultimately trading him to the Grizzlies as part of the deal to bring his older brother Pau to Los Angeles. Gasol's playing time, and therefore production, dropped precipitously two seasons ago when he was traded to the Raptors. Gasol will be 36 years old in January, and he'll be playing in a frontcourt with All-NBA Anthony Davis and Sixth Man of the Year Montrezl Harrell, so it's unlikely that his minutes or numbers will get any better with his move to the Lakers. Instead, he's now a late-round consideration in deeper fantasy leagues or, more likely, a waiver-wire candidate this season.

Bogdanovic turned in career highs in scoring (15.1 PPG) and 3-pointers (2.7 3PG) last season for the Kings to earn a huge free-agency deal this offseason with the Hawks. Bogdanovic was brought in to be a floor-stretching wing, who gives Trae Young more room to operate and knocks down the open looks that the dynamic point guard creates. The Hawks are poised to have a potent offense, and Bogdanovic could be on the verge of a career-best season.

Redick alternated between a starting and sixth-man role in his first season with the Pelicans, but he still maintained a mid-teens scoring average with 3.0 3-pointers per game. His shooting will be even more key this season, as the Pelicans build an offense around two elite forwards in Brandon Ingram and Zion Williamson, who will draw defensive attention and allow Redick many open looks. Redick's volume 3s make him a solid fantasy draft pick in roto leagues, and if he earns more minutes over newcomer Eric Bledsoe, he could have enough value to be worthy of a late-round selection in points leagues as well.

Holmes had a breakout campaign for the Kings last season, at least when he was healthy, averaging 12.3 PPG (64.8 FG%, 78.8 FT%), 8.1 RPG and 1.3 3PG in 28.2 MPG in 44 games, 38 of which were starts. This season, he faces stiff competition for playing time from newcomer Hassan Whiteside, with both of them too interior-oriented to play much together. Holmes is said to be working on his jumper, though, with an eye toward adding more 3-pointers to his repertoire. Holmes is worthy of a late-round flyer in fantasy drafts, in case he gets close to starter's minutes and is able to take the next step in his development.

Brooks is quietly coming off by far the best season of his young career, when he set new high marks with 16.2 PPG, 3.3 RPG, 2.1 APG, 2.0 3PG, 0.9 SPG and 0.4 BPG. Brooks projects as the scoring wing for the Grizzlies again this season, and his volume stats could be set to rise again, as he gets better looks playing off the ascending Ja Morant. Brooks is worthy of consideration late in fantasy drafts as a solid producer with genuine upside.

Young was one of the best offensive players in the NBA last season, ranking fourth in scoring (29.6 PPG), second in assists (9.3 APG), eighth in 3-pointers made (3.4 3PG) and second in offensive real plus-minus (plus-7.1). He enters his third season with high expectations and, with the addition of two excellent shooters in forward Danilo Gallinari and Bogdan Bogdanovic, should have more space to work and opportunity to set up teammates.

After a unique season trying to co-exist with James Harden on a Rockets team that required the full creative brilliance of both Daryl Morey to construct and Mike D'Antoni to coach, Westbrook will begin this season in a more traditional offense with a new Wizards squad. He will still be paired with a high-scoring shooting guard, but Bradley Beal operates off the ball to a much larger degree than Harden, which opens more possibility that Westbrook's game can mesh with him. Beal is more like a shooting guard version of what Kevin Durant was in Oklahoma City, and Westbrook and Durant were able to work together at a high level for years. The Wizards don't feature many high-usage players outside of Westbrook and Beal, so there may be room for both to operate without a big dropoff.

Williamson's rookie season was derailed before it began by a knee injury that kept him out for the first 44 games of the season. Even after he returned, he was on a minutes limit to keep him from aggravating his knee. Plus, in Williamson's own words, he was tentative when he returned, because he didn't want to make mistakes. Despite these limitations, Williamson still produced at an incredible per-minute pace on monster efficiency. Per 36 minutes, Williamson averaged 29.1 PP36 (58.3 FG%, 64.0 FT%), 8.1 RP36, 2.7 AP36, 0.9 SP36, 0.5 BP36 and 0.3 3P36 in 24 games. As a sophomore, Williamson has the potential to maintain a similar scoring pace and efficiency while playing more minutes. Also, Williamson averaged 1.8 BPG and 2.1 SPG in college, and those seemed to be the areas that were most afffected by his tentative play last season. If he can return to that type of defensive upside, Williamson has first-round fantasy basketball upside, even though he'll likely carry a second or third round ADP.

Gobert has been extremely consistent in his production during the past two seasons, with two-year averages of 15.5 PPG (67.9 FG%, 63.4 FT%), 13.1 RPG, 2.2 BPG and 1.8 APG. We know what to expect from him, and that production is worthy of consideration in the first few rounds of fantasy basketball drafts. Note, though, that ESPN's new points-leagues scoring gives less emphasis to efficiency and rebounding, so that works slightly against centers like Gobert. He's still an elite prospect, just not a borderline first-round pick.

Wall will return to the court this season, almost two full years removed from his last NBA game action, and he will do so on an entirely new team after being swapped for Russell Westbrook. Thus, two big questions arise. After recovering from his Achilles injury, what is the status of the explosiveness that once characterized Wall's game? And, how will Wall's preferred ball-dominant style play next to James Harden on the Rockets? Harden is an elite shooter, much like Bradley Beal was, but Harden operates more off the dribble than perhaps any shooting guard in NBA history. Wall doesn't have the jump shot to be maximized in an off-ball role, and he will have to learn to fit in next to Harden, as he joins the former MVP's team. In addition, will Wall have his minutes monitored as he returns? Will he play both ends of back-to-backs? Wall's upside makes him worthy of consideration relatively early in fantasy drafts, but those questions slide him down a few rounds from his previously lofty status.

Green peaked as a stats producer five seasons ago during the 2015-16 season, and both his per-minute production and overall minutes have gone down in each season since. Last season, Green struggled through injuries for much of the season and was less effective on the court with his superstar teammates from previous seasons all gone as well. This season, Green has some opportunity to bounce back to his ideal role as a star-complimentary player with Stephen Curry, Kelly Oubre Jr., Andrew Wiggins and even rookie James Wiseman called upon to do more scoring. This could free Green up to focus more on all-around numbers, where he can be a plus in assists, rebounds, steals and blocks while hopefully shooting better than the 38.9 FG% of a season ago, his worst mark since being a rookie.

This season, Wiggins will be called upon to join Kelly Oubre Jr. as strong off-ball finishers supporting Stephen Curry while also doing more dirty work on defense. Wiggins played 12 games in the Warriors' scheme last season, and the initial results showed some promise, as his 2-point field goal percentage of 51.2%, 1.3 SPG and 1.4 BPG would all represent career-best marks. And his 1.7 3PG and 3.6 APG combined with what he was doing pre-trade with the Timberwolves to set new career peaks as well.

Hield's role with the Kings is murky after a disjointed 2019-20 season. Prior to last season's All-Star break, Hield was the primary starting shooting guard for the Kings and averaged 20.4 PPG, 5.0 RPG, 3.8 3PG and 3.2 APG in 33.4 MPG. After the break, Hield was relegated to a bench role with decreased averages of 15.6 PPG, 3.2 RPG, 3.5 3PG and 2.1 APG in 22.9 MPG. The Kings have since lost Bogdan Bogdanovic, who had started over Hield, but drafted Tyrese Haliburton in this year's NBA draft. There have been reports about Hield clashing with head coach Luke Walton. It is unclear whether Hield will get his starting job back or if Haliburton or Cory Joseph might inherit the role. Hield will knock down 3-pointers at high volume no matter what, but his overall role will determine whether he's worthy of late-early-round fantasy draft consideration or instead more of a middle-round pick.

Lopez's production has been pretty stable with the Bucks the past two seasons, settling in with two-year averages of 12.2 PPG, 4.8 RPG, 2.3 BPG and 1.9 3PG in 27.8 MPG. It should be noted that his 3-point shooting dropped a bit last season, down to 31.4 3FG%, which was his lowest mark for the four seasons that he's been shooting at volume from long range. There is, therefore, a likelihood that he bounces back on that front this season -- especially with the addition of Jrue Holiday, an upgraded team offense creator who should get Lopez more open looks.

Grant averaged 14.1 PPG (48.4 FG%, 83.5 FT%), 4.3 RPG, 1.5 3PG, 1.3 BPG and 1.0 SPG in 24 starts with the Nuggets last season. This season, he projects as a starter for a talent-bereft Pistons squad that could afford him the opportunity for more volume, though likely at the cost of some efficiency. He is worthy of consideration in the middle/late rounds of your draft as an upside play.

Fultz got his career back on the right track last season with the Magic, earning the starting job and responding with starter averages of 12.2 PPG (47.4 FG%, 72.3 FT%), 5.4 APG, 3.4 RPG and 1.3 SPG in 28.7 MPG. He still needs to work on his 3-point range, as he turned in a dismal 26.0 3FG% as a starter, but on the whole, this was a major step forward from the struggles of his first couple of seasons with the 76ers. Fultz is locked in as the main lead guard for the Magic and has the upside to take a step forward this season in what is essentially his sophomore campaign. He offers solid value in the middle or late rounds of fantasy drafts.

Jordan battled injuries and came off the bench behind Jarrett Allen most of last season but still flirted with a double-double to go with his characteristically high field goal percentage and what was an unusually high free throw percentage (68 FG%). Jordan is likely to have a similar role this season, even if he may earn a bit more time next to his veteran friends Kevin Durant and Kyrie Irving. By this point in his career, Jordan's healthy production is pretty much set in stone.

Rozier came to the Hornets as a free agent last season and was expected to run the show, but instead, he took a back seat to the surprising break out of Devonte' Graham. This season, with LaMelo Ball and Gordon Hayward joining the squad, Rozier could find himself in more of a sixth man/spark plug off the bench that he once held for the Celtics. Rozier still has the opportunity to produce plus scoring, 3-point shooting, and perhaps better scoring efficiency, with better talent around him, but his volume as a scorer and especially as a distributor is more capped this season than last.

Dragic has battled injuries consistently for the past two seasons, which relegated him to coming off the bench in 56 of the 59 games he played last season. He still played close to starter's minutes, though, and averaged a robust 16.2 PPG with 5.1 APG, 3.2 RPG and 2.1 3PG in 28.2 MPG. Dragic moved into the starting lineup for the playoffs and stepped up his play, particularly his scoring, to 19.1 PPG in 32.5 MPG. His season ended a bit early due to a plantar fascia injury, but he claims to be fully healthy entering this season. If so, he is worth drafting in the middle rounds of drafts, sporting both the upside to outperform and risk due to his injury history.

Antetokounmpo is the two-time defending MVP, and with the Bucks still searching for their first NBA championship since the days of Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Antetokounmpo is still starving to get better. Plus, he will be freshly 26 years old when the season begins, so he still may not have reached his peak yet. The Bucks brought Jrue Holiday to town to help create team offense, which should open things up for Antetokounmpo to operate a bit easier on that end of the court. It could also allow him to put more energy into defense, where, despite winning the Defensive Player of the Year award, his steal and block numbers had decreased from his norm. The new ESPN scoring system places a premium on blocks and steals, so if he bounces back, it only further solidifies his strong argument as the top pick in points leagues.

Beal is coming off the best campaign of his career, when he averaged 30.5 PPG, 6.1 APG and 3.0 3PG with a respectable 45.5 FG% and 1.2 SPG, plus an excellent 84.2 FT% on 8.0 FTA. Based purely on his upside as he enters his potential peak at age 27, Beal would be a first-round prospect in fantasy drafts. However, he achieved these heights in the absence of long-time running mate John Wall, who missed the entirety of last season recovering from a ruptured Achilles tendon. Wall was traded to the Rockets, bringing back one of the highest usage players in the NBA in Russell Westbrook. Beal and Westbrook could potentially coexist well as an NBA backcourt because Beal is an excellent off-ball threat, but this arrangement almost certainly caps Beal's ceiling below what he could have produced as a solo act. Even so, he's still unlikely to get out of the second round of most fantasy drafts and has more upside in roto leagues than points, because his efficiency could increase next to Westbrook to counter some of the lost volume.

Irving has been elite support for LeBron James and the lead for a talented group with the Celtics. Now, he will attempt to be co-lead to Kevin Durant and a talented group with the Nets. Irving is the point guard, which means he'll have the ball in his hands as the decision-maker on most possessions, but for the Nets to succeed, his scoring volume has to decrease. His efficiency and assists could increase, though, so his biggest question marks aren't necessarily related to production but, instead, his health. Irving has missed at least 20 games in six of his nine professional seasons, and he played only 20 games last season.

Sabonis had a breakout campaign last season, averaging career highs across the board with 18.5 PPG, 12.4 RPG, 5.0 APG, 0.8 SPG and 0.5 BPG. Sabonis' season ended early due to a foot injury, but he is reportedly fully healthy entering this season and seems poised to pick up right where he left off as one of the dominant young big men in the NBA.

Harris had the best stretch of his career playing under Doc Rivers with the Clippers, averaging more than 20.3 PPG with a 48.7 FG% and 42.6 3FG% in 87 games. Harris will once again play for Rivers this season, on a team that is now emphasizing shooting surrounding stars Joel Embiid and Ben Simmons. Harris will be looked upon as the second scorer on the team and could be in for another career season.

Brogdon enjoyed a breakout season in his first campaign with the Pacers, averaging career-best marks with 16.5 PPG, 7.1 APG and 4.9 RPG in 30.9 MPG. He battled injuries throughout the season but returned to up those numbers to 21.5 PPG, 10.0 APG and 4.3 RPG in the first round of the playoffs. Brogdon is clearly the best team-offense creator on the team and is one of several plus scorers in the balanced Pacers attack. If Victor Oladipo returns to full health and his normal usage this season, it could eat a bit into Brogdon's opportunity, but on the whole, his trajectory as a player is upward.

Adams is coming off his smallest role in five seasons for the Thunder, down to only 26.7 MPG after having averaged 32.0 MPG in the previous three seasons. This offseason, he was dealt to the Pelicans, where he'll give them a huge, skilled defender and finisher to play next to the shorter and more versatile Zion Williamson. Adams will also make a good pick-and-roll partner for lead guards Lonzo Ball and Eric Bledsoe, and he should flirt with a low points-rebounds double-double with more than a block and steal per game.

Bogdanovic's 2020 season ended early with a wrist injury that sidelined him for the playoffs, but he has returned to practice for the Jazz and is expected to be ready to start the season. Bogdanovic averaged career highs of 20.2 PPG, 4.1 RPG, 3.0 3PG and 2.1 APG in 33.1 MPG in his first season with the Jazz, taking on the role of focal shooter in the frontcourt to space the floor for Donovan Mitchell and Rudy Gobert to work. He should reprise that roll this season, and if Mike Conley Jr. is healthy, Bogdanovic should benefit from being set up to shoot more consistently by a strong point guard.

Conley struggled through a nagging hamstring injury in his first season with the Jazz, which ultimately led to his worst statistical season in more than a decade. Conley eventually started getting healthy towards the end of February, and the extended break in the season seemed to help him even more once he got to the bubble. In the small sample of Conley's 11 games played between February 28 and August 8, he posted averages more similar to his norm, with 17.9 PPG (45.2 FG%, 94.6 FT%), 5.6 APG, 3.2 RPG, 2.7 3PG and 1.1 SPG in 33.1 MPG. Those numbers went up even further in his five playoffs games; 19.8 PPG, 5.2 APG, 3.6 3PG. Durability will continue to be a question for the 33-year-old Conley, but if healthy, he has a good chance to bounce back in his second campaign with the Jazz.

In some ways, Ball fits the mold of what the Hornets already had in the backcourt: an inefficient lead guard who can produce scoring and 3-pointers by taking a lot of shots. On the other hand, Ball is 6-foot-7 and has a rep as a gifted creator with true court vision and the type of charisma that a franchise could build itself around. His size will also allow him to play with either Devonte' Graham or Terry Rozier next to him, sharing some ball-handling duties and freeing him up to focus on scoring at times. Ball has a good chance to lead rookies in assists while battling for the lead in points and 3-pointers as well.

Bledsoe was somewhat miscast as a focal scorer with the Bucks, where he was asked to operate as a shooter playing off of the ball-dominant Giannis Antetokounmpo. With the Pelicans, he and Lonzo Ball will get to split the ball-handling, team offense creation and spot-up shooting responsibilities fairly evenly at one end while aggressively attacking opposing offenses at the other end. He remains a solid mid-round pick in fantasy basketball drafts in his new situation.

Carter's sophomore season was very similar to his rookie campaign, when he showed some promise as a potential nightly double-double player who can contribute about a steal and block per game, but he also struggled with injuries that limited him to just over 40 games played again. Carter is entering his third season and has the profile of a player who could break out if he's able to maintain his health.

Ingles had his lowest scoring output in three seasons and also saw year-over-year dropoffs across the board, as he shifted to a smaller role for the 2019-20 season. After starting 161 of the previous 162 games, Ingles came off the bench for 27 of the 72 games he played last season. He remained a steady all-around performer, averaging 5.2 APG, 3.9 RPG and 2.0 3PG along with 9.8 PPG. He seems likely to reprise a similar role this season, making him a later-round prospect in roto leagues but less likely to be drafted in points formats.

Beasley thrived after being traded to the Timberwolves last season, performing at a way-career-high pace with averages of 20.7 PPG, 5.1 RPG, 3.5 3PG and 1.9 APG in 33.1 MPG during his 14 starts. The Timberwolves added Ricky Rubio and No. 1 overall pick Anthony Edwards during the offseason and still have last season's sixth-overall draft pick Jarrett Culver in the fold, which will make it difficult for Beasley to get quite as many minutes and shots as last season. Also, he had legal difficulties this offseason that could result in some sort of suspension. With that said, Beasley's shooting separates him from the other wings on the team and fills a huge need, so he should get enough minutes to be worthy of consideration in the middle-to-late-middle rounds of fantasy drafts.
